    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/security/2013/11/bitcoins-skyrocketing-value-ushers-in-era-of-1-million-hacker-heists/?comments=1&amp;post=25759737" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">another ars account</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div data-orig-quote="<a href=&quot;http://arstechnica.com/security/2013/11/bitcoins-skyrocketing-value-ushers-in-era-of-1-million-hacker-heists/?comments=1&amp;amp;post=25759703&quot; class=&quot;postlink&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;>Wickwick</a> wrote:" class="quotetitle unsquish">show nested quotes</div><div style="height: 0px; opacity: 0;" data-orig-height="72" class="quotecontent">Not saying there's evidence of this, but since transactions are nearly untraceable, who's to say someone inside BIPS didn't orchestrate the whole thing?<br><br>Generally, when there's a physical robbery it's assumed to be an inside job until leads go elsewhere.</div><br>Except that bitcoins aren't that hard to <a href="http://www.technologyreview.com/news/518816/mapping-the-bitcoin-economy-could-reveal-users-identities/" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">trace</a>, apparently.  It seems to me that the only benefit of stealing them is inflationary; steal them and delete them, and your legitimate coins are more valuable.  Or only use them in places like Silk Road, and never try to exchange them for money.</div><br>That "trace" simply backtracks to the last transaction with an entity required to record the identities of the participants.  Similar to marked money.  You can see who deposits it in the bank and you can see who most recently took it out, but you are missing the 3 dozen people who used it for cash transactions between those two endpoints.  Marked money works because many of the first recipients turn it in to a bank which records the identity of the depositor.<br><br>To obfuscate the trail you transfer portions of the take to multiple wallets by anonymous transfer.  Then repeat the procedure with each of those wallets transferring to new wallets ... repeat the transfer a few hundred times, making sure the transactions overlap with each other and with money from legitimate sources that you have obtained through anonymous transactions.  (Computer scripts are wonderful tools) <br><br>This legit money blended with the stolen money over many fractional transactions, adds to the number of possible suspects as everyone identified as the last documented holder of a portion of the legitimate money has to be considered a suspect.  You are of course completely innocent and you had no idea that 200 transactions ago a portion of the BTC you received was stolen ... Oh what a shock!<br><br>In fact the money is recoverable if laws enable money whose blockchain identifies it as loot to be confiscated and returned to the last legal owner before the theft.  Of course that final holder after the theft has now been robbed, but (in theory) it at least spreads the losses over a large user base similar to the way innocent use of counterfeit robs the person holding the money when it is finally identified as fake money.
      
    </div>
    <footer>
      
      <span class="userinfo">1857 posts | registered <time class="reg-date">Sep 12, 2009</time></span>
    </footer>
  </li>						</ul>
			</section>
		
